question.generalfeedback:
a) Data for normality
  • The lowest value is \({@L[1]@}\)
  • The Lower Hinge is the 25th percentile: \(({@L[12]@}+{@L[13]@})/2\)
  • The Low-Spread is the difference between the lowest value and the median: \(({@L[25]@}+{@L[26]@})/2-{@L[1]@}\)
  • The Hinge to Extreme is the difference Lower Hinge-Lowest Value:\(({@L[12]@}+{@L[13]@})/2-{@L[1]@}\)
  • The Median is the middle number of the distribution: \(({@L[25]@}+{@L[26]@})/2\)
  • The Median to Lower Hinge is the difference Median-Lower Hinge: \(({@L[25]@}+{@L[26]@})/2-({@L[12]@}+{@L[13]@})/2\)
  • The Median to Upper Hinge is the difference Upper Hinge-Median: \(({@L[37]@}+{@L[38]@})/2-({@L[25]@}+{@L[26]@})/2\)
  • The Upper Hinge is the 75th percentile: \(({@L[37]@}+{@L[38]@})/2\)
  • The High-Spread is the difference between the highest value and the median: \({@L[50]@}-({@L[25]@}+{@L[26]@})/2\)
  • The Hinge to Extreme is the difference Highest value-Upper Hinge: \({@L[50]@}]-({@L[37]@}+{@L[38]@})/2\)
  • The highest value is \({@L[50]@}\)

b)
  • While there are no hard-and-fast rules for comparing figures such as those obtained here, many authors suggest that the figures should be within \(10%\) of each other before normality can be assumed. This is clearly not the case here. We conclude that the distribution of data being investigated is not symmetrical. In fact, the figures above suggest that the distribution is skewed to the left, a fact supported by the steam-and-leaf diagram of the same data to be found above. Remember that the term 'skewness' refers to the location of the 'tail' of a distribution.
